                    <msContents>
                        <summary>Miracles of Mary (Tä'ammərä
                            Maryam) and Miracles of Saint George (Tä'amərä Giyorgis)<p>Fols. 5r, 6v, 8r: States "Commissioned by Sofənəyos Akəlidewos".
                                </p><p> Large Arabic numbers added much later in pencil on bottom of
                                folios. </p><p> Fols. 58r, 67v: In the Miracle of Mary text, the
                                name of the owner/benefactor is listed as Särsä Micha'el. </p><p>
                                Fols. 68r, 73v: In the Miracle of Saint George text, the name of the
                                owner/benefactor is listed as Bəsə'a Giyorəgis. </p><p> Fol. 58r: A
                                note in another, later hand is the beginning of a letter draft, that
                                says "Letter sent from Bishop Mattewos, archbishop of the kingdom of
                                Ethiopia, servant and apostle of Christ, the son of Saint Mark."
                                Mattewos was bishop from 1889 to 1926. </p><p> Owner: Särsä
                                Micha'el, Bəsə'a Giyorəgis.</p><p> No scribe listed.</p><p> No
                                miniatures.</p><p> Gift of Bruce Willsie, Princeton Class of
                                1986.</p><p>How the Virgin Mary received the soul of Barok, a
                                dissolute man (incomplete) (Budge, Mary, 26; Strelcyn
                                32.16.26).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary accepted the book of her
                                miracles compiled by Saint Hildefonsus [Däqsəyos], Bishop of Toledo
                                (Budge, Mary 1; Strelcyn 15.1.1, 32.16.1; also commonly first in
                                medieval European collections).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary received
                                the soul of Anəsətasəyos) (Budge, Mary, 27; Strelcyn
                                32.16.27).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary spoke from her picture to a
                                devout worshipper (Budge, Mary 2; Strelcyn 15.1.3,
                                32.16.2).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary healed the Jew of Akəmim, an
                                elderly priest, when he fell and broke his back during his service
                                in her church (incomplete at the ending, folio missing) (Budge,
                                Mary, 03).</p><p>How Marəqos, King of Rome, fled from his palace for
                                the monastery for the love of the Virgin Mary.</p><p>How the Virgin
                                Mary appeared to the dying monk in the island of Tigris.</p><p>How
                                the Virgin Mary appeared to the widow and commanded her to recite
                                the "Hail Mary" (Budge, Mary, ?).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary appeared
                                to a priest named Yohannəs as a woman with wings like a
                                bird.</p><p>How the Virgin Mary saved the wealthy person from the
                                angels of darkness when he died.</p><p>How the Virgin Mary appeared
                                to a certain woman on the altar of the monastery.</p><p>How the
                                Virgin Mary saved Timothy, a drunken monk, from a lion and a mad dog
                                (Budge, Mary, 37).</p><p>How a certain Muslim was converted when he
                                saw oil and Myron from the breasts of the icon of the Virgin
                                Mary.</p><p>How the icon of the Virgin Mary in a certain church
                                bowed to the young person who served in the church and when he bowed
                                to her (Budge, Mary, 104, for a different version).</p><p>How the
                                Virgin Mary saved from death a governor of Eferan named
                                Armatəyas.</p><p>How the Virgin Mary appeared to the Bishop to
                                restore a priest called Enədrəyas who knew only the anaphora of the
                                Virgin Mary (Budge, Mary, 102).</p><p>How a certain king from Afəras
                                (France) named Niqodimos recited the Hail Mary his whole life and
                                when he died a tree with Hail Mary written on its leaves sprang from
                                his tomb (Budge, Mary, 38).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary saved from a
                                great snake Eskənədros the Jew from Jerusalem.</p><p>How the Virgin
                                Mary commanded a deacon to dig up and rebury in consecrated ground
                                the body of an adulterous deacon from the island of Jericho in the
                                city of Gärisat who was killed by the people (Budge, Mary,
                                103).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary saved Qiras the thief.</p><p>How the
                                Virgin Mary appeared to Isaac, the monk, and promised to take him to
                                herself after three days (Budge, Mary, 6).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary
                                appeared out of her picture to Mary, the daughter of a certain
                                God-fearing man from Dafra, to give her communion and promised to
                                take her to Paradise after three days (Budge, Mary, 7).</p><p>How
                                the Virgin Mary carried a sick person from the Monastery of the
                                Pilgrims to Jerusalem and showed him where Jesus was crucified and
                                buried and baptized him in the waters of the Jordan) (Budge, Mary,
                                9; Strelcyn 32.16.9).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary appeared to a Roman
                                youth called Zacharias who crowned her icon with roses and how she
                                saved him from bandits because they saw roses flowing from his mouth
                                when he recited her sälam and how they converted and became monks
                                (Budge, Mary, 10).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary recovered the stolen
                                property of two women called Juliana and Barbara, when they were on
                                pilgrimage to Jerusalem (Budge, Mary, 11; Strelcyn 32.16.
                                11).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary saved two Muslims from the storm when
                                they called on her name (Budge, Mary, 12; Strelcyn 32.16.
                                12).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary healed the eyes of Yohannəs Bäkänəsi,
                                the blind priest in Egypt, by anointing him with milk from her
                                breasts (Budge, Mary, 14; Strelcyn 32.16.14).</p><p>How the Virgin
                                Mary healed the merchant from Colossae after being shot in the eye
                                with an arrow by pirates (Budge, Mary, 15; Strelcyn 32.16.
                                15).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary restored the sight of Elizabeth, a
                                blind girl, with her breath and milk (Budge, Mary, 16; Strelcyn
                                32.16. 16).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary helped a wealthy woman from
                                Caesarea during a painful childbirth (not in Budge).</p><p>How the
                                Virgin Mary healed the foot of a widow from Harətärom) (Budge, Mary,
                                24).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary appeared to the Syrian potter and how
                                he glorified her (Budge, Mary, 35).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary gave a
                                child to a family in the country of the Europeans (Afərəng) in the
                                state of the French (Färansa) in and how she saved him from wrongful
                                accusation and a death sentence by hanging (Budge, Mary,
                                22).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary healed Bishop Märqorəwos of his
                                leprosy (Budge, Mary, 23; Strelcyn 32.16.23).</p><p>How the Virgin
                                Mary arranged marriages for two poor girls called Martha and Yäwahit
                                (Budge, Mary, 17; Strelcyn 32.16. 17).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary
                                aided in the delivery of a child to an abbess before the bishop came
                                to enquire into the matter (Budge, Mary, 25; Strelcyn
                                32.16.25).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary cut out and sewed a garment for
                                Filatawos, a bishop of the city of Sä'id in Upper Egypt (Budge,
                                Mary,40).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary received the soul of
                                Anəsətasəyos of Rome (Budge, Mary, 27).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary
                                moved the Monastery of Ekona (Budge, Mary, 13; Strelcyn 32.16.
                                13).</p><p>How Abba Samu'el levitated from the ground and spewed
                                fire from his mouth and was not touched by the rain when he read the
                                praises of the Virgin Mary (not in Budge).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary
                                interceded and returned a fallen angel to heaven.</p><p>How the
                                Virgin Mary and Jesus and the Angels came to Pifamon before his
                                martyrdom (not in Budge).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary helped a Roman
                                prefect when a mysterious ram prevented him from visiting Christ's
                                tomb until he had become a follower of the Virgin Mary (Budge, Mary,
                                39).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary rebuked a woman who gave up fasting
                                at her husband's command (Budge, Mary, 99).</p><p>How the Virgin
                                Mary delivered from prison a certain man called Giyorgis (Budge,
                                Mary, 19; Strelcyn 32.16. 19).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary protected
                                the elderly priest called Qätir from the church door keeper by
                                paralyzing the keeper (Budge, Mary, 20; Strelcyn 32.16.
                                20).</p><p>How the Virgin Mary raised the son of a certain man from
                                Capadocia (not in Budge).</p><p>How a certain rich man hurled a loaf
                                at the head of a beggar and wounded him, and how the Virgin Mary
                                delivered his soul from the devils) (Budge, Mary, 86).</p><p>How the
                                Virgin Mary saved the soul of the cannibal of Qəmər (Budge, Mary,
                                29; Strelcyn 32.16.29).</p><p>How Saint Giyorgis appeared to
                                Awəlogis and gave him a ship full of riches (incomplete at the
                                beginning, see 75r-77v for the beginning).</p><p>How Saint Giyorgis
                                removed a priest from his ministry who had stolen a gift from the
                                church and how he saved the priest from his sins. </p><p> Second
                                Miracle of Saint George is in a different hand.</p><p>How Saint
                                Giyorgis appeared as a builder to help the construction of the
                                church in Ləda during the reign of Constantine.</p><p>How Saint
                                Giyorgis punished Awyan, the commander of Dəyoqəltyanos, when he
                                destroyed the Church of St George in Jerusalem.</p><p>How Saint
                                Giyorgis appeared to Awəlogis and gave him a ship full of riches
                                (incomplete at the end, see 68r for the end of the
                                miracle).</p><!--BIBLIOGRAPHY--><p>References: See references in
                                manuscript no. 8. Regarding Miracles of Saint George, see Victor
                                Arras, Miraculorum S. Georgii Megalomartyris collection altera,
                                Louvain 1953 (CSCO 138,139); Encyclopedia Aethiopica, vol. 2, pp.
                                763-764.</p></summary>
